mk6gboot
--------

A tool to install/uninstall a dual bootloader into an iPod Classic 6G.


Usage
-----

  mk6gboot --install-bl <bootloader.ipod> [--pid <pid>]
  mk6gboot --uninstall-bl <bootloader.ipod> [--pid <pid>]
  mk6gboot --mkdfu <bootloader.ipod> <outfile.dfu> [--uninstall]
  mk6gboot --dfusend <infile.dfu> [--pid <pid>]
  mk6gboot --dfuscan [--loop [seconds]] [--pid <pid>]
  mk6gboot --dfureset [--pid <pid>]

Commands:
  --install-bl    installs bootloader.ipod into the device, if a
                  RB bootloader already exists then it is updated.
  --uninstall-bl  uninstalls bootloader.ipod from the device.

  --mkdfu     creates outfile.dfu, it is a DFU image containing
              an installer/uninstaller for bootloader.ipod.
  --dfusend   sends a DFU image file to the device.
  --dfuscan   scans for DFU USB devices and outputs the status.
  --dfureset  resets DFU device USB bus.

Options:
  -p, --pid <PID>   use a specific PID (Product Id) USB device,
                    if this option is ommited then it uses the
                    first USB DFU device found.
  -l, --loop [sec]  scan for a USB DFU device every 'sec' seconds,
                    default period ('sec' ommited) is 3 seconds.
  -u, --uninstall   create a file containing a DFU uninstaller.


<bootloader.ipod> is the code you want to install (a rockbox bootloader),
previously scrambled with tools/scramble utility. Command --mkdfu creates
a DFU imagen into <outfile.dfu> containing an installer (or uninstaller)
for <bootloader.ipod>, this DFU imagen should be send to the iPod using
--dfusend. The process can be abbreviated in one step using the command
--install-bl (or --uninstall-bl).



Dual bootloader installation
----------------------------

Windows:

  + An iPod Classic with Apple firmware installed and running, see list of
    current supported versions below.

  + The iPod must be formmated using FAT (Windows) filesystem, if your iPod
    is formated using Apple partitions you must convert this ipod to FAT32
    format (aka a "winpod"), see http://www.rockbox.org/twiki/bin/view/
    Main/IpodConversionToFAT32

  + If USB access is denied you will need to login as Administrator (or run
    the needed utilities as Administrator).

  * Yo must install the gerrit version of Rockbox (rockbox.zip) that matches
    the patch set of the bootloader.ipod that you are going to install. ATM
    the latest git versions of Rockbox doesn't work. Copy rockbox.zip to the
    root directory of the iPod and uncompress it.

  + If iTunes is installed:
    - configure iTunes to use the iPod as mass storage media.
    - close iTunes.
    - kill (or pause) iTunesHelper.exe

  + If iTunes is not installed, you must test if there is a valid USB driver
    installed, some Windows versions (i.e. Win7) includes (or automatically
    installs) drivers por Apple devices, other versions (i.e. XP) does not.
    - put your device on DFU mode and execute "mk6gboot.exe --dfuscan", you
      are expecting a result indicating that the device is found and the
      state is dfuIDLE (state=2).
    - if you received an error message, particulary like this:
        [INFO] winapi: no DFU device found
        [ERR] Could not open USB device: LIBUSB_ERROR_NOT_SUPPORTED
      it means that the device was found but there are no valid drivers
      installed, solve it installing one of these:
      - pre built WinUSB driver for emCORE (http://www.freemyipod.org/
        wiki/EmCORE_Installation/iPodClassic/DFUNoiTunes).
      - Zadig driver (http://zadig.akeo.ie/), not tested.
      - Apple Mobile Device USB driver (included with iTunes).

  + put you device on DFU mode, you can notice when the device enters DFU
    mode running "mk6gboot --dfuscan --loop" to scan the USB bus every 3
    seconds.

  + stop the previous --dfuscan command (if it is running) and send the DFU
    imagen to the iPod:
    mk6gboot --install-bl <bootloader.ipod>

  When the DFU is loaded it emits a 2000Hz/100ms 'alive' tone. When RB loader
  is successfully installed then 1000Hz/100ms+2000Hz/150ms beep sounds and the
  device reboots. If something went bad then 330Hz/500ms tone is emited and
  the device reboots. When an intermitent 330Hz tone sounds forever, it means
  that the NOR got corrupted and the device must be restored using iTunes
  (should not happen).

  Use the same process to update the RB bootloader if one is already installed
  into the iPod.

Linux:

  Same as above, skip the steps related to iTunes and USB drivers.


Supported FW
------------

1.1.2 (1G)
2.0.1 (2G)
2.0.4 (3G)
2.0.5 (4G)  *NOT TESTED*


Dual-Boot
---------

The purpose of this program is to provide dual-boot between the original
firmware and the new (rockbox) firmware.

Actually the button press check is done ~800 ms. after reboot, then:

  SELECT + MENU: enter DFU mode (it takes about 12 seconds)
  SELECT + LEFT: enter OF diagnostics
  SELECT + PLAY: enter OF diskmode
  SELECT + RIGHT: switchs the default FW to launch (Rockbox/Apple)
  Any other combination: launch default FW

Switch default firmware:

  Apple is the current FW:
  - stop playback and wait a few seconds for hard disk spin-down.
  - press and hold SELECT+MENU, after ~5 seconds the LCD powers off and the
    iPod resets.
  - once the screen goes black, wait for about 2 seconds (even more), then
    release MENU button and press and hold RIGHT button (CENTER button
    remains pressed), you have about 1 second for the release/press action.
  - the iPod should start to load RB firmware.

  Rockbox is the current FW:
  - power-off the iPod using Rockbox.
  - once the iPod is powered off, press and hold SELECT+RIGHT buttons, it
    is a bit tricky, try to press the buttons _firmly_, at the same moment
    (dificult thing) or to press the SELECT button _slighly_ early.
    The best way to solve this issue is not to switch to OF once you are
    using Rockbox as the default FW ;)
  - the iPod should start loading Apple firmware.


Hacking
-------

See comments in mkdfu.c, ipoddfu.c, dualboot.c and bootloader/ipod6g.c for
more information.
